{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "AerosolDistribution",
        "description": "ModelingToolkit implementation of a multi-modal lognormal atmospheric aerosol size distribution, from Seinfeld & Pandis (2006), Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics, 2nd ed., Chapter 8 (\"Properties of the Atmospheric Aerosol\"). The model represents the aerosol number, surface-area and volume distributions as a sum of three lognormal modes (Eq. 8.54), and reports the total number/surface/volume concentrations, the mode-1 Hatch-Choate diameters, and the vertical aerosol mass profile (Eq. 8.55). Migrated from Aerosol.jl AerosolDistribution. Purely algebraic: ten observed outputs, no differential states, an empty equations array. The upstream length-n_modes array parameters are scalarized at the default and documented n_modes = 3; default mode parameters are the Urban distribution of Table 8.3.",
        "tags": [
            "aerosol",
            "size-distribution",
            "lognormal",
            "seinfeld_pandis_ch8"
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "AerosolDistribution": {
            "reference": {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., and Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd Edition, John Wiley & Sons, Chapter 8, \"Properties of the Atmospheric Aerosol\". Multi-modal lognormal size distribution: Eq. 8.54 (number), 8.49/8.50 (surface area), 8.52/8.53 (volume); Hatch-Choate diameters Eq. 8.44/8.50/8.53; total moments Eq. 8.41 with Eq. 8.5/8.7; vertical mass profile Eq. 8.55; default mode parameters from the Urban entry of Table 8.3.",
                "notes": "source_ref: Aerosol.jl@c8c640bb636b22f2425460e9ed5cba50793bfee1:src/size_distribution.jl:25\n\nUpstream `AerosolDistribution(n_modes=3; ...)` is an MTK `@component` describing a multi-modal lognormal aerosol size distribution (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006, Chapter 8). It carries two `@constants` (pi_c = pi, ln10 = log(10)), the length-`n_modes` array `@parameters` N / D_g / logsigma plus the scalar `@parameters` D_p, rho_p, z, H_p, and ten time-indexed `@variables` (n_N_o, n_S_o, n_V_o, N_t, S_t, V_t, D_s, D_v, D_bar, M_z), each defined by one algebraic `lhs ~ rhs` equation. There is no `D(.)` time derivative anywhere.\n\nObservability classification: observed-form. Every one of the ten equation right-hand sides references only upstream `@parameters` and `@constants` — there is no upstream input `@variable` (connected input) on any RHS. Per the purely-algebraic migration rule, a component whose equation RHSs are parameter-only migrates in observed-form: each of the ten outputs is encoded as `type: observed` carrying its defining relation in the `expression` field, and the `equations` array is empty. This matches sibling parameter-only algebraic migrations (aqueous_eq.esm, gas_diffusion.esm, critical_ssa.esm).\n\nArray scalarization: the upstream N, D_g and logsigma are length-`n_modes` array `@parameters`. The component's default and documented configuration is `n_modes = 3` (a three-mode lognormal); the seven predefined distributions in the same source file (Urban/Marine/Rural/...) are all three-mode. The `.esm` array-variable path emits `getindex` nodes (tracked upstream as gt-p3ep), so this migration scalarizes the three modes into nine scalar parameters N_1..N_3, D_g_1..D_g_3, logsigma_1..logsigma_3 and unrolls each `sum(... for i in 1:n_modes)` into an explicit three-term sum. This is the faithful migration of the default three-mode component; the non-default n_modes are not represented.\n\nConstant handling: pi_c and ln10 are upstream `@constants`. The ESS schema has no constant variable type, so each migrates as a `type: parameter` with a fixed evaluated numeric default (pi_c = 3.141592653589793, ln10 = 2.302585092994046); the symbols are kept in the expressions. ln10 carries the conversion from the log10-based logsigma to natural-log form: ln(sigma_g) = logsigma * ln10, which is why the moment/Hatch-Choate factors read exp(k*(logsigma*ln10)^2).\n\nPruned parameter: the upstream `@parameter rho_p` (particle density, default 1500 kg/m^3) appears in none of the ten equations and is therefore not collected by `System(eqs, t)`. It is omitted from this migration per the unused-parameter rule — the model computes number, surface-area and volume distributions and a dimensionless vertical mass ratio, none of which require a density.\n\nDefaults: the upstream base `AerosolDistribution(3)` declares N, D_g, logsigma and D_p with no defaults (defaults are supplied only by the predefined wrappers such as `UrbanAerosol`). The docstring states \"Default parameter values correspond to the 'Urban' distribution from Table 8.3\", so this migration adopts the Urban Table 8.3 values as the defaults of N_1..3, D_g_1..3 and logsigma_1..3 (N converted cm^-3 -> m^-3 by x1e6, D_g um -> m by x1e-6). D_p defaults to 1.0e-7 m (0.1 um), the diameter the upstream test suite evaluates the distributions at; z = 0 and H_p = 1000 m are the upstream scalar defaults.\n\nTests: the nine inline tests below are translated from the upstream test suite test/size_distribution_test.jl. The single-mode upstream cases (AerosolDistribution(1)) are reproduced on the fixed three-mode .esm by zeroing the mode-2 and mode-3 number concentrations (N_2 = N_3 = 0), which removes their contribution to every sum; D_s, D_v and D_bar depend on mode 1 only by construction. Coverage spans all ten outputs, the three Table 8.3 presets (Urban/Marine/Remote continental), the lognormal peak and one-sigma points, log-space symmetry, the Hatch-Choate diameter ordering, the moment forms and the vertical mass profile.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-9): the component is purely algebraic with no ODE integration. Each output is a finite composition of +, *, /, ^, sqrt, exp and log10 in float64 (round-off ~1e-16 relative); rel=1e-9 leaves seven orders of magnitude of headroom and absorbs any associativity difference in the n-ary sums and products. The pinned expected values are the exact textbook-formula results, cross-checked at generation time against the closed-form Seinfeld & Pandis relations the upstream test suite asserts (peak = N/(sqrt(2*pi)*logsigma), the Hatch-Choate ratio D_v/D_s = exp(ln^2 sigma), the moment forms, M_z = exp(-z/H_p)).\n\nUnits: descriptive only; the ESS runners do no dimensional analysis. Units are copied from the upstream `unit` metadata verbatim (n_S_o / S_t in m^-1, n_V_o / V_t / M_z dimensionless)."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-09
            },
            "variables": {
                "π_c": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 3.141592653589793,
                    "description": "Pi (mathematical constant). Upstream MTK @constants entry pi_c = pi; the ESS schema has no constant variable type, so it migrates as a fixed-default parameter with the evaluated numeric value."
                },
                "ln10": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 2.302585092994046,
                    "description": "Natural logarithm of 10. Upstream MTK @constants entry ln10 = log(10.0); migrated as a fixed-default parameter. Converts the log10-based geometric standard deviations logsigma to natural-log form, ln(sigma_g) = logsigma * ln10."
                },
                "N_1": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 99300000000.0,
                    "description": "Total number concentration of mode 1 (nucleation). Upstream array @parameter N[1]. Default: Urban distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "N_2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 1110000000.0,
                    "description": "Total number concentration of mode 2 (Aitken). Upstream array @parameter N[2]. Default: Urban distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "N_3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "default": 36400000000.0,
                    "description": "Total number concentration of mode 3 (accumulation). Upstream array @parameter N[3]. Default: Urban distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "D_g_1": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1.3e-08,
                    "description": "Geometric median diameter of mode 1 (nucleation). Upstream array @parameter D_g[1]. Default: Urban distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "D_g_2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1.4e-08,
                    "description": "Geometric median diameter of mode 2 (Aitken). Upstream array @parameter D_g[2]. Default: Urban distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "D_g_3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 5e-08,
                    "description": "Geometric median diameter of mode 3 (accumulation). Upstream array @parameter D_g[3]. Default: Urban distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "logσ_1": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.245,
                    "description": "Log10 of the geometric standard deviation of mode 1 (nucleation) (dimensionless). Upstream array @parameter logsigma[1]. Default: Urban distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "logσ_2": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.666,
                    "description": "Log10 of the geometric standard deviation of mode 2 (Aitken) (dimensionless). Upstream array @parameter logsigma[2]. Default: Urban distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "logσ_3": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.337,
                    "description": "Log10 of the geometric standard deviation of mode 3 (accumulation) (dimensionless). Upstream array @parameter logsigma[3]. Default: Urban distribution, Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Table 8.3."
                },
                "D_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1e-07,
                    "description": "Particle diameter at which the number, surface-area and volume distribution densities n_N_o/n_S_o/n_V_o are evaluated. The upstream base AerosolDistribution declares D_p with no default; 1.0e-7 m (0.1 um) is adopted here — the diameter the upstream test suite evaluates the distributions at, in the accumulation-mode range."
                },
                "z": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Altitude above the surface, used by the vertical mass profile M_z. Default 0 m (surface). Upstream @parameter z = 0.0."
                },
                "H_p": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1000.0,
                    "description": "Aerosol mass scale height in the vertical profile M_z = exp(-z/H_p). Default 1000 m. Upstream @parameter H_p = 1000.0."
                },
                "n_N_o": {
                    "type": "observed",
                    "units": "m^-3",
                    "description": "Number distribution density dN/d(log D_p) at the evaluation diameter D_p — the sum of n_modes lognormal modes (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006, Eq. 8.54).",
                    "expression": {
                        "op": "+",
                        "args": [
